@NODE 1. "Distribution"

    P96_TurboSVD is MailWare.

    You are allowed to copy it, or redistribute it  free  of  charge,
 but I wonder how many people use it ;-)

    You can get the source files (100% asm) if you are a  programmer,
 and only if these files may help you to finish or  enhance  some  of
 your program (you'll have to prove that).
    These files should not be redistribute, modified nor reused, what
 ever reason you'll have.

@ENDNODE

@NODE 2. "Installation"

                              @{b}Installation@{ub}

    The easiest way  is  to use the Installer script.  It copies the
 driver into ShapeShifter's @{i}Video drivers@{ui}  directory,  and a catalog
 translation file into the @{i}Catalogs@{ui} directory.  This catalog is only
 used to translate error messages and thus is not mandatory.
@ENDNODE

@NODE 3. "Usage"

                                @{b}Usage@{ub}

    Start ShapeShifter, then open the graphic setup window. Select the
 color depth  you  want  to  use  and  turn the driver type gadget  to
 @{i}External@{ui}.  Select  the  P96_TurboSVD  driver,  then choose the screen
 mode.  Next, adjust the refresh rate  according to your CPU power and
 the screen mode. All screen modes may need a refresh.

    @{b}68020/68030@{ub}  users  should  use  a  high  value  for  refresh rate
 because the  whole screen  has  to  be redrawn each time.  You should
 select "Amiga mouse cursor" too, otherwise the cursor will jump every
 time.

    @{b}68040/68060@{ub} users may use a value of 1, because of the increase in
 speed due to the MMU.  Please read the ShapeShifter documentation for
 more  information  about  this.  The  @{i}Refresh always@{ui} and @{i}MMU refresh@{ui}
 check boxes don't have to be checked.

 @{b}NOTE:@{ub}  Refresh modes need a lot  of memory. If ShapeShifter complains
 that  there is not enough memory,  you should probably use a  8  bits
 color  depth,  or  lower  the  memory requirement for ShapeShifter to
 leave more Amiga memory for the screen.
@ENDNODE

@NODE 4. "Refresh information"

                          @{b}Refresh information@{ub}

   You  will probably want to use  the fastest display mode, but  this
 may  not always be possible. Because  the display speed is based upon
 your  CPU power,  the color format used,  the gfx board and the Zorro
 bus, you should test all possible solutions to find which is the best
 configuration on your system,

   The  driver  always  tries  to  achieve  the  maximum  speed.   The
 information below may help you to figure  out  what happens  when you
 use one display mode or another.

   @{b}68020/68030 :@{ub}  Only  CLUT,  RGB15  and  ARGB  color  formats  don't
 require any refresh. All other color formats require refresh.

   @{b}68040/68060 :@{ub} If you use a ZorroII gfx board, @{b}@{u}all@{uu}@{ub} color formats are
 refreshed to avoid uneeded ZorroII accesses.  If you have a  ZorroIII
 gfx board, the driver never  refreshes  the  Mac native color formats
 (CLUT, RGB15 and ARGB).
@ENDNODE

@NODE 5. "Memory usage"

                              @{b}Memory usage@{ub}

    The table below  show how  many bytes  are needed  for the buffers
 (800x600). You can see that the driver may need a lot of memory...

                                        QuickDraw  Delta buffer @{b}TOTAL@{ub}
 8 bits screen depth without refresh  :   480000          0    @{b}480000@{ub}
 8 bits screen depth with refresh     :   480000     480000    @{b}960000@{ub}
 16 bits screen depth without refresh :   960000          0    @{b}960000@{ub}
 16 bits screen depth with refresh    :   960000     960000   @{b}1920000@{ub}
 24 bits screen depth with refresh    :  1920000    1440000   @{b}3360000@{ub}
 32 bits screen depth without refresh :  1920000          0   @{b}1920000@{ub}
 32 bits screen depth with refresh    :  1920000    1920000   @{b}3840000@{ub}

 NOTE : The Delta buffer is no longer used when you have a Zorro III
        gfx board and either a 68040 or a 68060. Then, the memory is
        equal of the QuickDraw buffer size (v1.4)

@ENDNODE

@NODE 6. "Bugs"

                                  @{b}Bugs@{ub}

 None found yet.
 The  driver was  currently tested  with A4000/060/PicassoIV Picasso96
 v1.22a, ShapeShifter 3.8

  You should send bug repports to me via E-Mail only. Please tell me :
 · What is your machine? (A1200/A2000/A3000/A4000)
 · Which CPU you have (68020/68EC030/68030/68040/68060)
 · The amount of memory you have and how much is used by ShapeShifter.
 · The Picasso96 and ShapeShifter versions.
 · Your Gfx board (along with its type: Zorro II/III)
 · ...and anything else :-)

@ENDNODE

@NODE 7. "History"

                                @{b}History@{ub}

    @{b}v1.2@{ub} (17.3.97)  First public release.

    @{b}v1.3@{ub} (24.4.97)  Second public release.
    · Full source clean-up. Most parts are reworked.
    · Use  040/060  MMU to  support screen  switching, only if the Gfx
      raster  memory is  succesfully aligned.  This would  be the case
      since   Picasso96  release  1.14.  @{b}THIS  WON'T  RUN@{ub}  with  older
      versions. Screen switching support means that ShapeShifter  @{b}WILL
      NOT CRASH@{ub} your other screens anymore !
    · Use  SaveFunc()  and  RenderFunc()  with all screen modes  (less
      memory consumption).
    · Add RGBA and BGRA conversion  functions. These color formats are
      used when available instead of RGB24 (or BGR24).
    · Add  a  conversion function  for  ZorroII Gfx  boards  (for non-
      refresh  modes) when  the  user  has  a  68040/68060  (for speed
      reasons)
    · The driver is now localized (Error messages)
    · Added an optimized refresh function for 68020/68030.  Speed gain
      goes from +24% to -33%  (speed loss occurs only in special  cir-
      cumstances)
    · Disable interrupts while playing with MMU translation tables.
    · Use MOVE16 again  (040/060 only)  when I backup/render the whole
      raster.
    · Check  the  Picasso96API  version  number   (and  not  only  the
      revision)
    · Added some requesters which  may help the user  to  get the best
      speed from the driver.

    @{b}v1.4@{ub} (28.7.97)  Third public release.
    · Bug fix : The driver didn't complain when  ShapeShifter  has  to
      use a refreshed screen mode, and the Delta buffer was not  allo-
      cated.
    · The delta buffer is no longer allocated if you have a  Zorro III 
      gfx board and a 68040 or a 68060. Huge refreshes will be faster,
      but this slow things down when there are only some pixels to re-
      draw
    · Very little optimization of LoadRGB32()
    · Updated this documentation.
@ENDNODE

@NODE 8. "Future"

                                 @{b}Future@{ub}

  · 68030 MMU support.
    I can't do it myself, so...

  · Perhaps more optimizations, if it is possible... ;-)

  · Memory defragmentation (for driver's buffers only)
    Nobody ask me about that

  · ShapeShifter's screen in a PIP window.
    This may be done, but only with a hack. (Discard ?)

 BTW, ShapeShifter 3.8 now has an internal driver for Picasso96, which
 makes TurboSVD useless in most cases.

 So, if I have to release a new version, this will be probably for :
 - Bug fixes.
 - 68030's MMU support.
 - QuickDraw support if Christian Bauer is kind enough to make this
   use possible with an external driver...

@ENDNODE

